[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Issue 2: Safety Constraint Ordering Allows Contradictory Outcomes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **File:** `chapter15.07-python-example.md`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Location:** Step 3 (`apply_safety_constraints`), Constraint 5 (renal contraindications)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Severity:** WARNING (misleading pattern for readers)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Description:** Constraint 3 (min duration hold) may set `safe_action = current_level`, but Constraint 5 (renal) runs afterward and can override it to `safe_action = 0` (lifestyle only). This means a patient who hasn't been on their current treatment long enough could still get switched to lifestyle-only due to renal function, bypassing the "give it time" logic. While clinically this might be correct (contraindications override duration holds), the code doesn't explain this priority ordering. A reader implementing their own constraint system might not realize that later constraints can override earlier ones, leading to unexpected behavior.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Suggested fix:** Add a comment before Constraint 5 explaining the priority:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   # Constraint 5: Renal contraindications.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   # NOTE: Contraindications override duration holds (Constraint 3) because
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   # safety trumps "give it more time." If eGFR drops below threshold while
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   # on metformin, the drug must be stopped regardless of duration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
